    "human": "I asked a founder last week to send me their last five churned-customer exit interviews.\n\nBefore I opened them, I asked him: “Who do you think you lost these deals to?”\n\nHe named two competitors. Real companies, funded, logos I recognized. He’d built a whole competitive matrix around them - feature checkboxes, pricing comparisons, a battle card his sales team was supposed to memorize.\n\nI opened the exit interviews. Here’s who he actually lost to:\n-\n\n“We just kept using the spreadsheet, honestly.”\n-\n\n“Our ops person handles it manually, it’s fine.”\n-\n\n“We never really got around to fully switching over, so we just… didn’t.”\n-\n\n“Our intern does this once a week, takes her like an hour.”\n-\n\n“Nothing changed, we just stopped prioritizing it.”\n\nZero out of five lost to a competitor. Five out of five lost to the status quo.\n\nThis is almost always true, and almost nobody believes it about their own business - myself included. I’ve built this exact battlecard before, more than once. At my last startup, I could tell you our competitor’s pricing, their last three feature launches, and the name of their VP of Sales. I could not have told you, without being forced to go dig through exit interviews, that the actual thing beating us was a shared Google Sheet three different customers had independently built to do 80% of what we did, for free, badly, forever.\n\nWhy we obsess over the wrong competitor\n\nCompetitors are legible. They have websites, pricing pages, Twitter accounts, funding announcements. You can screenshot their new feature and slack it to your team with a panicked “did you see this?!” It feels like real, urgent, actionable information.",
    "ai": "Your biggest competitor probably isn't who you think it is.\n\nI see founders spend hours mapping out competitor decks, tracking their pricing changes, obsessing over feature parity.\n\nMeanwhile, the thing actually killing their deals?\n\nThe spreadsheet their prospect has used for 5 years.\nThe manual process nobody loves but everyone tolerates.\nThe \"we've always done it this way\" mentality.\n\nThe status quo doesn't need a marketing budget. It doesn't need a sales team. It just needs inertia—and inertia is a powerful, patient opponent.\n\nHere's what this means in practice:\n\n→ Your pitch shouldn't just be \"better than Competitor X.\" It should answer: \"Why change at all?\"\n\n→ Your real sales cycle isn't fighting for market share—it's fighting apathy, risk-aversion, and \"maybe next quarter.\"\n\n→ The switching cost isn't just money. It's the mental energy of learning something new, the fear of disruption, the political capital of championing change internally.\n\nI've watched startups win against well-funded competitors and lose to nothing—to a prospect simply deciding the current (worse) way was safe enough.\n\nSo before you obsess over the competitive landscape, ask:\n\n- What does life look like for my customer if they do nothing?\n- Am I selling a better solution, or am I selling change itself?\n- Have I made the cost of inaction visceral and clear?\n\nThe startups that win aren't always the ones with the best product. They're the ones who understand that status quo bias is the default setting of human behavior—and they design their entire GTM motion around overcoming it.\n\nStop only watching your competitors. Start studying inertia.\n\nThat's the real fight.\n\n---\n\nWhat's been your experience—have you lost more deals to competitors or to \"no decision\"?",
