    "human": "I saw this study from METR this week and I have not stopped thinking about it since. They had experienced developers use AI tools to do real coding tasks. Afterwards, the devs said, yeah, that felt like I was about 20% faster. Cool. Except when they actually measured it, these developers were 19% slower. Not a typo. Slower. They felt fast. They were not fast.\n\nOkay, so here's what I think is actually going on, broken into a few pieces.\n\nOne, the vibe lies. Feeling fast and being fast are two completely different measurements, and most of us are only checking the first one.\n\nTwo, this is not even a new story. It just has an AI costume on. When factories first switched from steam power to electricity, everybody assumed productivity would skyrocket overnight. Flip the switch, boom, efficiency. It took 30 years. Three decades. Because the problem was never the power source, it was the layout. Every machine was arranged around one giant steam engine and a system of shafts and belts. Electricity let you put a small motor on every single machine, but nobody redesigned the floor plan for decades. They just swapped the engine and expected magic.\n\nThree, that's exactly what's happening with AI right now. People are bolting a chatbot onto the exact same workflow they had before and wondering why the whole thing doesn't feel transformed. You didn't redesign anything. You just added a really fast, really confident intern into a process that was never built to use them well.\n\nSo here's what I want you to actually do. Pick one task you do regularly, something you've used AI on and assumed is saving you time, and time yourself doing it with AI and without it. Not a feeling, an actual stopwatch.\n\nTry it this week and let me know in the comments what you find. I have a feeling some of you are going to be surprised.",
